<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 92 / International Company News: Child World freezes credit
payments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHILD WORLD, which claims to be the second largest discount toy retailer in
the US, revealed yesterday that it has stopped paying trade creditors and
landlords of its 125 stores.
The troubled company said payments were being 'delayed,' although a
spokesman declined to say when they might restart.
Child World, based in Massachusetts, made the delayed payments public in
conjunction with an announcement that it was 'entering discussion on new
sources of equity financing'. It maintained the object of holding up
creditor payment was to 'ensure that day-to-day operations continue to run
smoothly'.
The retailer added that its banks had entered 'an amendment and limited
waiver' in relation to an existing credit facility, which constrict the
facility to the amount outstanding for the next fortnight, in order to give
time for the discussions to take place.
Child World's financial problems last came to head in late-1990 when
payments to creditors were also temporarily halted. However, in June 1991,
the retailer's former owner - CNC Holding - sold its 82 per cent interest in
the struggling company to an investor group led by two former executives of
Toys 'R' Us, the largest retailer in the field.
Under the deal, toy manufacturers were to receive sums over a number of
years. This schedule had begun and was continuing until the current freeze
of trade creditors payments became operative.
Speculation that Child World, which operates stores under the Child World
and Children Palace names, might be unable to make payments circulated last
December, but a payment was made mid-month.
</TEXT>
