<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 92 / International Company News: Steinhardt in Dollars 587m bid
for Integrated Resources
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
STEINHARDT Managers, the New York-based investment company, yesterday
announced that it had made a Dollars 587m cash bid for Integrated Resources,
the troubled financial services company in Chapter 11 bankruptcy.
The Steinhardt bid matches a similar offer for Integrated from the Pritzker
family of Chicago, whose holdings include the Hyatt Hotel chain.
The new offer comes a few weeks after Bankers Trust, the US banking group,
pulled out of a deal to acquire Integrated for Dollars 565m, reported to be
because negotiators could not agree on the terms of the liabilities the bank
would have assumed under the takeover.
Steinhardt said its bid was submitted on behalf of the company and
'affiliated entities' last week.
It would not comment on the details of the offer, but said it expected its
proposal to be subject to significant negotiations and modifications.
Any acquisition of Integrated would have to be approved by the bankruptcy
court and creditors as part of a reorganisation plan that brings the company
out of Chapter 11.
Integrated, which specialised in syndicating property tax shelter
partnerships, went bankrupt in February 1990 with liabilities of at least
Dollars 1.5bn.
Since then, the company has been talking with a number of potential bidders
while attempting to formulate a reorganisation plan.
Steinhardt Partners is an investment and fund management firm run by the New
York money manager Mr Michael Steinhardt.
The company was in the news last year after it was discovered that
Steinhardt was one of the customers which, along with securities house
Salomon Brothers, acquired more than 90 per cent of a May 1991 auction of
government securities.
Government authorities are investigating whether there was any collusion
between Salomon and its customers to corner the market in the May issue.
Some market participants claimed they lost millions of dollars because of
Salomon's dominance of the two-year note issue, and their complaints
eventually led to the discovery of illegal bidding by Salomon's bond trading
desk in previous auctions.
The investigation, however, has so far uncovered no evidence of such
collusion, and Steinhardt Partners has repeatedly denied any wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
