<PROFILE>_AN-CCCA8AFFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920303
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 92 / UK Company News: Curious similarity leads GrandMet to
Dollars 500m suit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WHAT'S THE difference between a 'Curious Kid' and a 'Burger King Kid'? Far
more than a hamburger may rest on the answer.
Grand Metropolitan, the food and drink group which owns the US-based Burger
King chain, has become the target of a US lawsuit which claims that the
cartoon characters used to promote the Burger King Kids Club were copied
from an earlier cartoon called 'The Curious Kids'.
The plaintiff is CK Company, a general partnership linked to a small New
York-based company called Gould &amp; Reichman and which holds the copyright to
the Curious Kids characters.
The damages claimed are anything but modest. CK is asking for Dollars 500m
(Pounds 286m).
The nub of the CK case is that the Burger King Kids have mimicked many of
the Curious Kids features.
One character in both strips is in a wheelchair; one is an Afro-American
boy; there are three Caucasian boys in each, and two Caucasian girls.
The Curious Kids have a dog called Morty, the Burger King Kids one called
Woofer. Both 'gangs' play musical instruments, and have one boy and one girl
vocalist - Kid Vid and Boomer in the case of Burger King, or David and
Tracey for the Curious Kids.
CK brought similar allegations to Burger King's attention in July 1991, when
they were investigated. GrandMet has not seen the suit, but believes it is
without merit.
The lawsuit says the Curious Kids were devised 'to teach elementary science
concepts and reading skills and focus on social issues.' The Burger King
Kids Club is used as a marketing tool.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 26
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-5572</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CCCA8AFEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920303
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 92 / UK Company News: Deal simplifies ADT
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL ASHCROFT, the controversial head of ADT which yesterday sold its
indirectly held 49 per cent stake in Cope Allman Packaging, might be
forgiven for crowing.
The sale places a Pounds 117m price tag on the stake which many analysts
have found extremely difficult to value. Not only does it reduce ADT's debt,
more importantly, it clarifies parts of ADT's often complicated
relationships with affiliate companies which have created misunderstanding
and suspicion among shareholders, and markets in general.
Yesterday's 37p rise in the share price to 500p reflects the value of the
deal to ADT.
It is possibly the first good news ADT has had to announce after last year's
public fight with its largest shareholder, Laidlaw, and a grim period of
watching the falling values of investments in companies like Lep and
Christies.
ADT is not receiving the Pounds 117m in cash immediately. At completion
Bowater will pay Pounds 58m in cash with a further Pounds 9m over three
years. In addition Bowater will give ADT a Pounds 50m transferable and
interest bearing loan note.
After the cash, this aspect of the deal is the most valuable to ADT. Instead
of holding Pounds 102m in loan notes of uncertain value from Quoteplan, the
subsidiary which owned Cope Allman, it now has marketable Bowater paper.
ADT sold its 49 per cent stake in Quoteplan to Sechura, its Canadian
affiliate, in 1990 for CDollars 90m, (Pounds 43m), financed by loan notes
from ADT.
At the last interim stage, ADT wrote down the value of its Sechura loan
notes. As a result it is understood ADT will have to make only a small
write-down on these notes. Sechura, where Mr Ashcroft and his wife now have
a 29 per cent stake, will then be an empty shell with no assets and no
liabilities.
The end of ADT's Sechura chapter should go some way to clearing up what had
become something of a hallmark of the Ashcroft way of management - the
shuffling of assets between ADT affiliates and related companies which pass
the auditors' scrutiny but leave shareholders and the City somewhat
suspicious.
In the 1990 accounts, for example, ADT did not take a 49 per cent share of
Quoteplan's Pounds 10.3m net attributable loss into its own profit and loss
account. Instead it took a profit on the sale of Quoteplan to Sechura.
The sale also profitably ends Mr Ashcroft's involvement with Quoteplan which
started with a failed bid in 1983 and led to a leveraged buy-out in 1988 at
a time when debt financing was readily available.
Had Quoteplan been floated at some future date - the intention was to float
last December but market conditions were not propitious - ADT might have
shared a slice of a larger pie.
But few shareholders worried about ADT's debt would begrudge Mr Ashcroft
acceptance of Bowater's offer. Had he not, ADT would still now be the
largest creditor to a debt-laden business, neither a fashionable position to
be in these days nor consistent with Mr Ashcroft's new strategy of reducing
gearing.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
