<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 92 / UK News (Employment): Union complains of rise in attacks at
benefit offices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VIOLENT attacks on staff in unemployment benefit offices and Jobcentres have
increased by 50 per cent since the removal of protective screens began in
1989, the CPSA Civil Service union said yesterday
The union warned that long-standing industrial action could intensify unless
the removal process was halted.
Publication of the figures is the latest move in the dispute over the
government's decision to move to open-plan offices without security screens
or counters. The industrial action, which started in April last year, has
cost the union Pounds 1m.
The CPSA dispute involves about 100 benefit-office staff who have have been
on strike for nearly a year in Bristol, Newcastle upon Tyne and London.
There was also a one-day national strike last November and other lightning
strikes.
The union wants security arrangements in offices to be negotiated locally,
with independent assessment of risks at offices before security arrangements
are altered. It has called on the Health and Safety Executive to act.
Mr John Macreadie, CPSA general secretary, said: 'At the same time that
counters and security screens are being removed, the frustration of
claimants and job seekers is growing. We have a lethal cocktail of anger and
despair and this is no time to strip our members of security.'
The union said there had been 233 attempted and actual physical assaults in
1990. It predicted that the level would turn out to have been maintained
last year and would rise. Before screens and counters were removed, the
number was 155.
The employment department disputed the union figures, saying there were 118
physical assaults in 1989, 161 in 1990 and 152 last year. Its figures do not
include attempted assaults.
The Bifu bank workers' union last week produced figures showing that raids
on banks and building societies in London had doubled over the past year.
Bifu is pressing for more and better security screens.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 14
</PAGE>
