<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 92 / UK News (Employment): Furniture workers consider a merger
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FTAT, the furniture union, has held exploratory talks with several large
unions including the TGWU general workers' grouping about a merger.
Mr Colin Christopher, FTAT general secretary, said the recession 'has
knocked us sideways'.
The union lost 10 per cent of its membership last year and expects to go
into deficit next year for the first time since the mid 1980s. Many larger
unions would be interested in a merger because of its 32,000 members and
considerable assets.
'We are still financially sound, but we have to look to the future and that
might have to include a merger,' Mr Christopher said. 'We are just fishing
around at the moment.'
He believes the greatest industrial logic lies in a merger with the Ucatt
construction union. But talks between the two have been called off because
of organisational difficulties within Ucatt.
FTAT has also spoken to the MSF technical union and the GMB general union,
and talks are planned with the Usdaw shopworkers' union.
Mr Christopher said FTAT would be 'a very attractive asset' for any large
union, but stressed that, because of their craft tradition, members would
not want to lose their identity in a merger and would expect to be offered
their own section.
</TEXT>
