<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 92 / Legal action to recover losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OVER THE past two years several thousand Lloyd's Names have taken legal
action to recover insurance losses. They are suing their agents or the
Lloyd's Corporation, the body which provides regulatory and market back-up
services.
Actions settled recently
Some 500 Names on Warrilow 553 won a Pounds 4m out-of-court settlement
including legal costs on February 7 (represented by Elborne Mitchell).
A group of 987 Names on Outhwaite syndicate 317/661's 1982 year won a Pounds
116m out-of-court settlement on February 12 (Richards Butler).
Actions under way
A group of 33 Names is suing Lloyd's alleging it negligently failing to
close the Oakeley Vaughan agency before the syndicates it managed ran up
heavy losses (Michael Freeman).
About 175 Names from Aragorn syndicate 384's 1985 year agreed to take legal
action last week in a bid to recover insurance losses (Macfarlanes).
Writs have been issued and served in three other cases. More than 400 Names
on Pulbrook syndicate 90's 1982 year; more than 320 of the 570 Names on
Pulbrook 334 in 1985; and more than 400 of the 800 Names on Poland
syndicates 105 (1985 year) and 108 (1986 year). All three groups are advised
by solicitors DJ Freeman and are alleging breach of contract and
misrepresentation by members' agents and negligence by managing agents.
At least 91 US Names allege Lloyd's breached US securities laws when they
were recruited. They are represented by Proskauer Rose, the New York firm.
Cases in Denver and Chicago are being fought by individual Names. In Canada
about 70 Names - represented by the Toronto law firm McCarthy Tetrault - are
in the midst of a case against Lloyd's. They are appealing against a verdict
in Lloyd's favour on a preliminary issue, but have so far successfully
prevented banks from drawing down their deposits.
More than 600 Names on Feltrim, Devonshire, Gooda Walker and Rose Thomson
Young syndicates, represented by Michael Freeman, are issuing motions to
seek an injunction preventing Lloyd's from drawing down their deposits.
Injunctions are against agents - following the decision by Lloyd's to
contest the action. Agents have agreed to freeze deposits until court
hearings. These are expected around March 26.
Possible actions
Gooda Walker Names Association has asked both Withers and Michael Freeman to
represent its members.
Feltrim Names Association (Richards Butler).
Devonshire Names Association (Norton Rose).
Rose Thomson Young (Withers).
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 12
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-5597</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CCCA8AEPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920303
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 92 / Lloyd's ball bounces in the solicitors' court: A look at the
complex collection of cases being prepared on behalf of anxious Names
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THESE are busy times for Mr Michael Freeman, senior partner in a small
solicitors' firm in London's West End.
Last week he was in the House of Lords arguing a technical point of law
arising from a legal action he is conducting on behalf of 33 Lloyd's Names
from the defunct 1981-82 Oakeley Vaughan syndicate.
The Names - individuals whose capital backs underwriting at the Lloyd's
insurance market - claim Lloyd's was negligent in not closing down Oakeley
Vaughan and that it failed to warn them of an unfavourable internal report
on their syndicate and its underwriters.
Mr Freeman was also busy co-ordinating an action on behalf of more than 600
Names to prevent Lloyd's drawing on the cash deposits or bank guarantees
individuals put up to cover loses when they become Names. This move
threatens to compromise the market's ability to meet claims.
The position was complicated by the decision of Lloyd's to defend the
action. but Mr Freeman has to issue individual writs on behalf of each of
the Names involved.
Mr David Coleridge, chairman of Lloyd's, has warned Names that the actions
will fail and add legal costs to the bills they already face. He has also
said that Lloyd's would meet insurance claims over the next month that would
otherwise be met from the funds deposited by Names, and that Names would
eventually have to meet the cost. Faced with heavy losses, many Names cannot
afford a protracted legal battle.
Many lawyers in the City feel that Mr Freeman's action is unlikely to do
more than delay the inevitable - but this may not matter.
What Names want most, say many lawyers, is some form of settlement which
avoids the need for them to take protracted legal action and offers
financial help with their losses. They argue that Lloyd's faces legal action
from disgruntled Names on so many fronts that it could crash unless a rescue
package is mounted soon to provide the cash to meet outstanding claims.
Mr Guy Sutton, a partner with City solicitors Norton Rose, is co-ordinating
claims by 150 Names who belonged to the Lime Street members' agency, which
has ceased trading. Their claims are typical of potential lawsuits by Names.
The allegations about Lime Street include failure to follow instructions,
professional incompetence in placing husband and wife Names on the same
high-risk catastrophe reinsurance syndicates, and the placing of Names on a
higher proportion of high-risk syndicates than was prudent.
Some Lime Street Names have joined actions against the syndicates run by
Feltrim and Gooda Walker. Most of those actions - like the recently settled
Outhwaite litigation - turn on the issue of underwriting negligence. For the
rest the only course has been to instruct Norton Rose to write to Lloyd's
and request an inquiry into Lime Street.
That letter was sent in December, and Lloyd's has set up five inquiries into
the biggest loss-making syndicates in 1988, the latest year to report. But
Norton Rose says Lloyd's has done nothing about Lime Street except refer the
case to its professional conduct department.
Mr Sutton believes the crisis at Lloyd's is so serious that the government
or the Bank of England will have to step in and provide the cash needed for
Lloyd's to pay claims. That would be followed by a rescue scheme allowing
Names to escape liability for some losses and pay the remainder over a
period of time.
He says a rescue package is unlikely to come from 'mutualisation' -
spreading losses among Names who have made money in recent years. They will
be reluctant to pick up the tab for others they feel have been misinformed,
misled or just plain foolish.
'It is very important for the City that Lloyd's survives,' Mr Sutton says.
'To be honest, if it wasn't for the fact that we are facing an imminent
election I would have expected some kind of rescue to have been organised by
now.'
Lawyers themselves have not escaped without blame. There is a view growing
in the City that the only people who stand to gain from the present
situation were the lawyers. Cynics suspect that in these recessionary times
lawyers are only too willing to encourage actions against Lloyd's.
This is a little unfair. One thing law firms do not lack in a recession is
litigation work. Firms involved in the Lloyd's lawsuits are also, with the
possible exception of Michael Freeman, recognised insurance experts.
Norton Rose is one of the UK's top 10 law firms by size, and is rated in the
top three for commercial litigation. Richards Butler and DJ Freeman are also
in the top 50 by size, and Elborne Mitchell is in the top 100 in London.
Few Names faced with losses could afford the Pounds 250 to Pounds 300 an
hour normally charged by these firms. Because the Names' circumstances vary
so much there is no prospect of clubbing together in a group action.
If lawyers become bogged down in protracted litigation on behalf of Names,
there is a very real prospect that, if they are paid, it may be at a vastly
reduced rate. That would render the work barely profitable.
Many of the Lime Street Names who clubbed together to instruct Norton Rose
to write to Lloyd's have joined the litigation against Lloyd's launched in
November by New York lawyers Proskauer Rose under the US 'no win, no pay'
contingent fee system.
In the UK it appears to be in everyone's interests to reach an out-of-court
settlement. If the government does not mount a rescue scheme, there may be
much to be said for the suggestion from Mr Ian Hay Davison, former deputy
chairman and chief executive of Lloyd's, that an effective arbitration
process might provide the best way out.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
