FT  03 MAR 92 / Government U-turn on plans for A1
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT yesterday announced its conversion to the idea that the A1
road between Newcastle upon Tyne and Edinburgh should be upgraded to dual
carriageway, James Buxton writes.
The transport department and the Scottish Office previously said the section
did not justify upgrading with only 20 per cent of traffic between England
and Scotland using it - although there are plans to upgrade the A1 from
London to Newcastle from dual carriageway to motorway.
Yesterday Mr Malcolm Rifkind, transport secretary, and Lord James
Douglas-Hamilton, Scottish Office roads minister, said they had concluded
that 'it would be desirable for the A1 to be fully dualled from Edinburgh to
Newcastle'.
Work on the project is due to start in May but no date was given for
completing it.
The ministers pointed out that construction work on making a section near
Berwick-on-Tweed dual-carriageway would begin by the end of May and that
other such schemes were being developed. Four small projects to ease
overtaking at blackspots on the Scottish section of the route are to be
studied. The total cost of schemes in progress or under consideration is
about Pounds 110m.
Campaigners on both sides of the border who have recently highlighted the
number of accidents on the single-carriageway road said that the statement
was 'little more than a pre-election gimmick'.
</TEXT>
