FT  03 MAR 92 / Computer software research wins Pounds 25m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government is putting more money into research on ensuring that computer
software does what it is supposed to do and does not do anything that could
endanger life or the environment.
Yesterday it said an extra Pounds 6m would be made available to the
four-year Safety Critical Systems Programme run by the Department of Trade
and Industry and the Science and Engineering Research Council.
The funds are part of a Pounds 25m package announced yesterday to improve
software technology and applications, and brings to Pounds 36m the value of
the safety-work scheme.
Computer software is notoriously difficult to test for errors because of its
complexity and the number of different ways a computer can react to
differing circumstances. Fears that software controlling sophisticated
machinery may contain undetected errors have been highlighted by the crash
in January of an A320 Airbus, controlled by complex computer systems, even
though no errors were found in the software.
The DTI announced yesterday that Pounds 11.7m would be made available for
research into 'co-operative' working - allowing people in different
locations to work on the same information at the same time.
A further Pounds 7.5m was pledged to work on open, or industry-standard
systems to make different manufacturers' computers compatible. These are
increasingly seen as the pattern of the future.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
