<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 92 / Parliament and Politics: Government defeat on inspectors -
Education Bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT may be forced to abandon efforts to hand responsibility for
the inspection of schools over to school governors after being 'ambushed' by
Labour peers last night.
In the surprise result of a vote on the Education (Schools) Bill, the Lords
decided by 95 to 67, a majority of 28, to amend legislation intended to
allow parents to choose school inspectors.
A second government defeat pushed through Labour's alternative proposal to
pass control from local education authorities to the national schools
inspectorate.
The vote represents a serious embarrassment to the government, which has
repeatedly trumpeted the controversial changes as a cornerstone of its
policy to shake up education by devolving powers to parents.
Commenting later, Mr Kenneth Clarke, the education secretary, said: 'We will
have to decide what to do.
'If the Bill is of a form consistent with the Parent's Charter we will take
it through the Commons. If it is not, we will try to amend it.'
Labour has been widely expected to make political capital from attacking the
concept of 'privatised' inspections as a triumph of political dogma over
common sense.
Nonetheless, the government's defeat is an unwelcome reminder to its
business managers of the Conservatives' vulnerability to surprise attack.
While the Opposition may support other clauses, there are now doubts as to
whether there will be time to reverse last night's defeat if an April 9
election is called.
Before the vote, Baroness Blatch for the government warned the peers that
the amendment sought to 'tear the heart out of the bill'.
Afterwards, Mr Jack Straw. Labour's education spokesman, said: 'The bill was
a piece of wreckage before this defeat and now it is well on the way to
being sunk.'
Government ministers must now decide whether to attempt to reverse the
defeat next week, to accept the changes, or to abandon the inspection
elements in the bill.
</TEXT>
