<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 92 / Parliament and Politics: Labour reverses Tories' poll
advantage - Public Opinion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NEIL KINNOCK, the Labour leader, is a step closer to becoming prime
minister, if the latest Financial Times compilation of opinion polls is an
accurate forecast of UK voting intentions.
The slim advantage for the Opposition party over the Tories would be
sufficient to deprive the Conservatives' of an overall majority in the
Commons. If Mr John Major resigned, Mr Kinnock could try forming a minority
government or agree a pact with the smaller parties at Westminster which
would hold the balance of power.
The latest weighted average, which takes account of the differing sample
sizes of the seven polls covered, puts support for Labour about half a
percentage point ahead of the Tories - almost reversing a similar lead the
Tories had in the survey last week.
If the results are transformed into numbers of MPs, the distribution of
support for the two main parties would still make the Conservatives the
largest party with 305 seats. Labour, however, would have only three seats
fewer. The Liberal Democrats would have 19, up one from last week.
Since last week's poll of polls Tory support has slipped by about one
percentage point while the Liberal Democrats have risen by about the same
amount. Labour's standing has remained at about 39 per cent. The survey,
however, highlights how evenly balanced support for the two main parties
remains, despite frenetic campaigning since the beginning of the year. The
difference between the two is well within the margin of error.
The only clear trend is a steady rise in support for the Liberal Democrat
party, although its standing is still not high enough to suggest its
parliamentary representation will stay as high as its current 22 MPs. Labour
at present has 230 Commons' seats and the Conservatives 367.
</TEXT>
