FT  03 MAR 92 / Noriega met CIA chief after he saw Castro
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HENRY HAMMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MIAMI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Reagan administration's director of Central Intelligence, the late Mr
William Casey, met Panama's General Manuel Antonio Noriega in 1984 less than
a month after the general visited Cuba to meet President Fidel Castro.
The hitherto unreported meeting was acknowledged by Mr Donald Winters, CIA
station chief in Panama from June 1984 until the summer of 1986, testifying
yesterday for the defence in Gen Noriega's drug trafficking trial in Miami.
Mr Winters said yesterday the CIA had 'encouraged and appreciated' the
assistance of Gen Noriega, particularly in passing on information about Cuba
and President Castro. His testimony forms part of the defence effort to
portray the general as a US ally.
Mr Noriega's meeting with Mr Casey was one of at least four with CIA
officials held immediately before and after his overnight visit to Havana on
July 5 1984.
