FT  03 MAR 92 / Iraqis to put case before UN delegates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON and AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN Iraqi delegation led by Mr Tariq Aziz, the country's deputy
prime-minister will come to New York next week to speak to the UN Security
Council on March 11 about scrapping Baghdad's weapons of mass destruction,
UN diplomats said yesterday.
The Security Council said last week Baghdad had less than two weeks to
explain its position and comply with ceasefire accords mandating the
scrapping of all weapons of mass destruction.
President Saddam Hussein would otherwise face undetermined 'serious
consequences,' the council said.
British officials said the meeting would show Iraq that anger at its
prevarication over the UN resolutions is shared across the 15-member council
and 'that it's not just the case that the whole show is being run by the US,
backed by Britain and France'.
Iraqi is expected to argue that the economic embargo against Baghdad should
be lifted in parallel with compliance with the UN resolutions. The Security
Council will insist, however, that the embargo must remain in force until
Iraq has complied in full with its orders.
In Baghdad, Mr Aziz said Iraq had pursued the 'objective, accurate
implementation of (UN) measures'.
He said he would tell the council Iraq would approve if the UN aimed to
implement Resolution 687. 'But if your objective is to annihilate Iraqi
industry and deny Iraq the chance of becoming a prosperous industrial
country, that would be a different matter.'
Baker acted on loans, Page 7
