<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 92 / Yeltsin moves to support German autonomous area
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RUSSIAN President Boris Yeltsin signed a decree yesterday that supports the
restoration of a German autonomous republic on the Volga river, Russian
television said, Reuter reports from Moscow.
'The document draws attention to the necessity of urgent measures to
rehabilitate and, step by step, to restore the statehood of Russian Germans
inside the Russian Federation,' the television said.
Soviet leader Josef Stalin accused the Volga Germans, descendants of workers
brought to Russia by Tsar Peter the Great and Empress Catherine the Great in
the 18th century, of collaborating with invading Nazi troops in 1941.
All were deported to Siberia and Central Asia, and now more than 800,000
ethnic Germans are scattered across Russia. The decree suggests the first
step is to set up a German national district in the Volgograd and Saratov
regions.
Mr Yeltsin promised to restore the German republic when he visited Germany
last year.
President Yeltsin will start a two-week working holiday in the Black Sea
resort of Sochi,his press secretary said.
</TEXT>
