<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 92 / MPs hit at City over pensions regulation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CITY'S system of self-regulation over pension funds will bear the brunt
of fierce criticism by a cross-party Commons committee next week over its
failure to prevent the disappearance of several hundred millions of pounds
from companies controlled by the late Robert Maxwell.
In particular, the Select Committee on Social Security is expected to single
out the Investment Management Regulatory Organisation (Imro) for allowing Mr
Maxwell to control a fund management company that gave him personal access
to his employees' pension funds.
The MPs are expected to recommend radical changes in UK pension law. They
may possibly call for pensions to be run by trustees employed by independent
companies unrelated to the employer, rather than the present system where
employers often select trustees.
MPs contend that, in its testimony to the committee, Imro had failed to
persuade them that it had exercised good judgment in authorising Mr
Maxwell's companies to operate as fund managers or that it had supervised
them properly.
The comments come as Imro's latest report to its members reveal that 66
members - roughly 5 per cent of the total - are under investigation because
investors' money may be at risk.
Maxwell company pensioners have targeted Imro's failure to spot the Maxwell
abuses in a fresh campaign to win compensation from the government. The
Maxwell Communication Pension Plan Consultative Committee is urging all
members to write to their local MPs citing Imro's decision to authorise Mr
Maxwell's Bishopsgate Investment Management as a 'fit and proper body'.
The report will also criticise some City bodies, particularly actuarial
firms, for failing to take sufficient responsibility over the affair.
The Commons committee's report had been scheduled for publication on
Thursday but the volume of additions sought by MPs and the time spent
yesterday debating its broad thrust has forced a delay until Monday.
The committee, which will meet again tomorrow, is hoping to make its
conclusions more powerful by agreeing as much as possible without dissent
among members.
The pensions industry, shaken by the revelations about the Maxwell affair,
is supporting calls by politicians for reform.
The National Association of Pension Funds (NAPF), the industry's largest
trade association, has called for changes in the composition of boards of
trustees and changes in rules over custodianship.
During weeks of testimony, actuaries, accountants, lawyers and former
pension fund trustees told the committee that they did not know the true
state of the pension funds' finances or their investment policies. They also
said they had no responsibility for investigating further.
The Institutional Fund Managers Association, the trade association
representing those who invest pension funds, has endorsed the NAPF
proposals.
The Institute and Faculty of Actuaries last week called for a review of
pension law, saying that the current trust law governing pension funds may
no longer be sufficient.
Mr Roy Brimblecombe of Clay and Partners and chairman of the institute,
said: 'One of the problems with trust law is its absence of teeth.'
MPs on the committee have yet to decide whether the role played by banks in
some of the share transactions involved was sufficiently culpable to merit a
wider attack on the City. The committee is also understood to be considering
calling for a compensation scheme for pensioners.
In addition, the committee will report to the Commons on the failure of Mr
Ian Maxwell and his brother Kevin to reply to a questionnaire sent by the
committee to the pension trustees.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 1
</PAGE>
