<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 92 / Parliament and Politics: Prescott publishes motorists'
charter - Transport
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday sought to counter suggestions that it is the anti-car party
by publishing a charter for motorists.
The 31-point plan, produced after consultation with motoring organisations,
sets out proposals for giving better consumer protection to motorists and
tightening up on road safety.
Mr John Prescott, shadow transport secretary, said private motor cars were
'an indispensable and inescapable fact in the quality of life of millions of
people in modern Britain'.
He denied suggestions that an incoming Labour government would axe the
Department of Transport's Pounds 20bn roads programme to pay for a big
increase in spending on public transport: 'What we are talking about is a
six-month moratorium on the placing of new road-building contracts to give
us time to decide a new order of priorities.'
Labour would replace separate planning for investment in roads, railways and
air transport with a single transport infrastructure programme spanning 20
years.
Common criteria would be adopted when deciding which means of transport to
invest in. Most important of these would be improving mobility, reducing
environmental damage and relieving congestion.
For car users, proposals in the motorists' charter include:
A central record of the make and model of vehicles involved in accidents, so
figures can be used to rank the safety of different cars.
Insurance companies should be required to notify all accident claims to the
Driver and Vehicle Licensing Centre. Prospective purchasers of second-hand
cars would then be able to check a vehicle's history for a small fee.
Vehicle mileages should also be notified to the DVLC when they are MoT
tested. It should be illegal to use a hand-held mobile telephone while
driving. Tax incentives on company cars would probably be phased out. Labour
argues this would lower the price of new cars to private buyers by
eliminating big fleet purchases.
Quality Motoring. The Labour Party, 150 Walworth Road, London SE17 1JL.
Free.
</TEXT>
