<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 92 / Guinness trial juror defends role of juries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Financial Times Reporter
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LEADER of the jury in the second Guinness trial, which collapsed
recently, has rebutted widespread claims that the trial was too complicated
for juries to understand.
Mrs Edna Wijeratna, in an unusual public statement on the growing debate
over the handling of complicated City trials, blames the length of the trial
on the decision by Mr Roger Seelig, one of the defendants, to conduct his
own case.
She also reports that members of the jury wondered whether 'the
consideration extended to Mr Seelig would have been forthcoming for a
defendant in humbler circumstances'.
The government is considering urgent reforms to English fraud law following
the conclusion of a number of big City trials, including the Blue Arrow
case, which cost an estimated Pounds 35m, the second Guiness trial and
Barlow Clowes.
Mrs Wijeratna's views are set out in a letter to the Financial Times.
In it she asserts the jury had no undue difficulty in understanding the
details of the case, contrary to the view of many legal experts.
'Members of the legal profession have a way of writing about juries as if it
were universally recognised that they are composed of people vastly inferior
in understanding to their august selves.
'This seems to bear no relation to reality, at least as far as Guinness II
is concerned.'
Mrs Wijeratna says it is unusual for a jury member to comment publicly about
a case. But she was aware that people were arguing that it would be better
to take fraud trials out of criminal law altogether.
She writes: 'Surely the legal profession will have failed society if a thief
ceases to be considered a thief, or a cheat a cheat, provided he operates
with sufficient sophistication.' Mrs Wijeratna says the jury's main
frustration was not with the complexity of the 4 1/2 -month trial, but with
the slow rate of progress caused by the decision of one of the defendants,
Mr Seelig, to conduct his own defence.
The judge ended the trial on February 11 after psychiatrists reported that
Mr Seelig was suffering from severe mental, physical and emotional strain.
Letter, Page 15
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
