<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 92 / Sharp rise in theft insurance payouts: Insurers association
says recession may be causing a rise in fraudulent claims
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THEFT INSURANCE payments rose by more than 60 per cent for domestic
properties and 20 per cent for commercial premises to a total of more than
Pounds 800m last year, according to figures to be released by the
Association of British Insurers next week.
The ABI, which represents most UK insurers, will also announce that fire
damage payouts last year rose to Pounds 1.02bn, half of which is thought to
be due to arson. About Pounds 100m of this, it believes, resulted from
policy holders setting fire to their own property to claim insurance money.
Other heavy lossmaking categories include theft of and from cars, where
claims rose by 50 per cent, and mortgage indemnity policies which compensate
lenders for losses when their properties are repossessed.
The figures for 1991, described by the ABI as a 'diabolical year' for its
members, highlight the background of recession and rising crime against
which Royal Insurance and Commercial Union last week announced heavy UK
underwriting and pre-tax losses.
Results from other insurers in coming weeks are expected to be similarly
poor; General Accident, which reports tomorrow, says 1991 was 'pretty
horrendous' for UK insurers.
Insurers have also noted the public is following the US by becoming more
compensation-minded: 'if it moves, sue it' summarises one insurer. People
driven by recession into frugality are also making claims when previously
they did not bother, and insurers are facing heavy payouts to redundant
workers with unemployment protection policies.
Faced with increases in legitimate claims, insurers are taking a tougher
line on fraud, says the ABI. While last year's fire claim total is just 1
per cent up on 1990 - a decrease after inflation  - the ABI believes
fraudulent arson may be rising as businesses continue to struggle.
Forensic scientists acting for insurers now sometimes arrive at fires before
the flames are doused. The increase in arson has also bred forensic
accountants who check the finances of fire-stricken companies. Insurers, who
suspect many more cases of fraudulent arson than they can prove, record
details of large fires against a checklist, says Mr Nigel Lister, General
Accident's UK assistant general manager.
Tell-tale signs include: a switched-off fire alarm system, lack of evidence
of a break-in, fires which start in several places and at night in an empty
building, non-payment of bills by the company and prior removal of stock.
Soft-heartedness is a giveaway; a guard dog's unaccustomed absence is
significant.
In one recent case a London corner-shop owner, desperate about competition
from a new superstore, lit rubbish behind the counter, locked up and went
home.
The shop was destroyed and its owner jailed for 18 months. Some attempts are
amateurish; an East Anglian furniture importer burnt down his warehouse
before discovering his insurance was not paid up. 'It becomes more difficult
when they bring in the professional gangs which are undoubtedly operating
around the country,' says Mr Lister.
In the past insurers were reluctant to delay payouts: 'claims settlements
are our shop window,' says one. Mr Lister says that, where companies now
withhold payment because fraudulent arson is strongly suspected, claimants
nervous of court hearings often suggest much-reduced settlements.
Other arsonists are vandals, thieves, dishonest staff destroying evidence of
crime and disgruntled employees.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 16
</PAGE>
