FT  02 MAR 92 / Handling of economy 'appalling'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government's 'appalling mismanagement' of the UK economy will prolong
the recession throughout this year according to economists at Liverpool
University, Edward Balls writes.
The latest forecast from Liverpool Macroeconomics Research expects output to
fall by 0.4 per cent this year, with only a weak recovery in the final
quarter. Unemployment is projected to reach 2.9m by the end of the year, and
depressed demand for imports is expected to push the current account back
into surplus.
Professor Patrick Minford, director of the group, said the recession was
being prolonged because UK economic policy was 'paralysed by the exchange
rate mechanism'. The ERM was keeping interest rates high, in spite of
falling inflation and low monetary growth. The group expects retail-price
inflation to fall to an annual 2.9 per cent in 1992.
Prof Minford is a member of the group of 'Liverpool Six' monetarist
economists who have repeatedly called on the government to cut interest
rates and leave the ERM.
Mr Bill Martin, chief economist at UBS Phillips &amp; Drew and one of the six,
endorsed the forecast, describing the outlook as 'decidedly bleak'.
Forecast Vol 13, No 1 March 1992. University of Liverpool, PO Box 147,
Liverpool L69 3BX.
