<PROFILE>_AN-CCBBHADNFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920302
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 92 / Budget 92: In search of clues to the elusive 'feel good'
factor - Business confidence is hard to create and even harder to define.
Unlike inflation and interest rates, the mood of business cannot be
precisely measured
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE 'feel good' factor
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
or lack of it  - can win or lose general elections. With business confidence
falling rapidly, time is running out for the government. Economic indicators
are unlikely to show any great improvement before the election, so the
government is pinning its hopes on fostering an optimistic mood with a
tax-cutting Budget on March 10.
That may not be as easy as it sounds. Confidence is elusive - hard to create
and even harder to define. Unlike inflation and interest rates, the mood of
business and consumers cannot be precisely measured and fed into computer
models. When the economist John Maynard Keynes used the expression 'animal
spirits', he captured the intangible nature of what makes businesspeople
tick.
Put simply, it is to do with expectations. If entrepreneurs expect good
markets they invest and a bandwagon of growth takes off.
The Confederation of British Industry has tracked business confidence since
1958 by asking companies whether they are more or less optimistic about
prospects than they were three months before and by plotting the difference
to give an optimism index.
The index reached its lowest point of - 75 in January 1974, a month after
the announcement of the three-day week. One of its highest points since 1958
was June 1963 (+53), when Harold Wilson began his 'white-heat-of-technology'
general election campaign.
The CBI says the most important determinant of general business optimism
identified in its survey is the level of orders. Interest rates rank second,
with exchange rates and political conditions at home ranked equal third.
But what effect can a hot summer, a big sporting success, Big Bang, or the
end of a war have on that elusive 'feel good' factor?
If you are looking for a consumer-led recovery, events such as a royal birth
or a World Cup win are a good thing, says Professor Nigel Nicholson,
director of the Centre for Organisational Research at the London Business
School.
'But you can only buck the market for so long, and there are always going to
be global economic forces at work at the same time,' he adds.
Professor Douglas Mc-Williams, economic adviser at the CBI, considers
outside factors to be 'surprisingly unimportant' in defining business
confidence against the evidence company managers see with their own eyes. A
company is confident when it is meeting its budget targets and loses
confidence when it falls short, he says. Only in the former instance will a
company be inclined to spend in the short term.
Similarly, Mr Ian Thompson, economic adviser at the Engineering Employers'
Federation, points to activity at a micro-level when he defines business
confidence. 'There could be a pick-up in business confidence when destocking
comes to an end as the end of destocking brings orders for companies back up
again,' he says.
Activity at a micro-level constitutes the more tangible end of what
influences confidence. But what of the other factors beyond company and
factory walls that are said to hold sway over confidence?
One of the problems of conducting a survey of confidence is that respondents
tend to reflect their own hopes in the answers they give to questions about
prospects for turnover.
Mr Kevin Gardiner, an economist at merchant bank SG Warburg, believes
businesses are influenced by national issues such as whether sterling should
be devalued, the level of house repossessions and the general election.
'People who fill in the CBI surveys watch the media as much as anyone else
and are going to be influenced as much as anyone else,' he says.
Mr Clive Thomson, chief executive of Rentokil, the London-based timber
treatment and services business, agrees.
'I think the media influences business confidence a great deal,' he says.
'If you read or see people expressing gloom or despondency it is very
difficult to maintain a positive stance.'
Mr Richard Brown, co-ordinator of a survey of business confidence carried
out by the Association of British Chambers of Commerce, believes that when
confidence started to rise in the third quarter of last year there was a
feeling that the respondents were being 'egged on' by comments the
chancellor was making about 'green shoots of recovery'.
His critics would call this 'jawboning' - attempting to create a mood by
talking the economy up or down, an unlikely way of encouraging growth. As Mr
Geoff Unwin, executive chairman of computer consultancy Hoskyns Group, says,
confidence has to be based on a sound belief.
'Unfortunately the government has cried 'Wolf' too often - if someone keeps
saying that the economy is going to get better next month and it never does,
you end up not believing them,' he says.
This year an obvious uncertainty affecting confidence is the general
election.
Mr Paul Droop, an economist at the Ernst &amp; Young Item Club, which draws up
forecasts of the economy using the Treasury's computer model, says the
election is bad for optimism. 'If there is a change in government there
could be a change in policy, so no one really knows what to expect.'
But it is the uncertainty rather than the outcome that appears to be
stifling decisions.
Mr Malcolm Blackburn, the managing director of Otter Controls, a thermostat
manufacturer in Buxton, Derbyshire, says his company did just as well under
Mr Harold Wilson as it did under Mrs Margaret Thatcher. He says that big,
one-off events are more likely to influence confidence than changes of
governments.
'We felt optimistic about the Common Market in the 1970s because it meant
the disappearance of export duties - that was an optimistic period. But the
oil price shock worried us because we are a very large user of nylons, which
are oil-based.'
Mr Gardiner at Warburgs points to the absence on the horizon of any such
one-off confidence boosters. He says: 'Looking further into the 1990s, we
are going to see eastern Europe opening up - but that is a long way off at
the moment.'
But if the Budget fails to boost confidence, there could be another saviour
for the Conservative party - and the longer the election is delayed the more
effective it will be. It is the weather.
Mr Unwin is a great believer in the weather. 'People just generally feel
better when the weather is better,' he says. 'I think it was a contributory
factor to Heath losing the election in February 1974 - it was snowing, it
was cold and everybody felt bloody miserable.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 7 Graph (Omitted). Illustration (Omitted).
</PAGE>
