<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 92 / Warning of increase in inflation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUDGET plans for tax cuts or higher public spending on infrastructure
investment could lead to higher inflation and unemployment unless combined
with a policy of co-ordinated wage restraint, a leading left-of-centre think
tank argues today, Edward Balls writes.
An expansionary Budget is needed to prevent unemployment rising to 3m this
year, according to the Institute of Public Policy Research.
Such a Budget should include a short-term programme of maintenance of
schools, hospitals and council houses, it says.
Central government restrictions on the ability of local authorities to build
new homes should also be lifted.
Yet boosting demand could lead to a renewed bout of wage and price inflation
unless unions and employers agree to limit pay settlements, the report
argues.
The institute says the government should open talks with employers and
unions in order to draw up a pay policy. Any workable strategy would have to
contain an agreement on the desired 'going rate' of pay settlements and the
circumstances under which exceptional increases could be allowed.
Full Employment In The 1990s. IPPR, 30-32 Southampton Street, London WC2.
Pounds 7.50.
