<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 92 / Companies express interest in providing BR rail services
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MALCOLM RIFKIND, transport secretary, yesterday said that about 12
private companies had expressed interest in providing various rail services
when British Rail's network monopoly is broken, Gary Mead writes.
He said the government 'will end British Rail's monopoly because there are
already about a dozen British companies who want to provide new services,
both freight and passenger'.
Mr Rifkind said that one reason why private investment might be sought was
poor performance by some sections of British Rail.
Among those interested in participating in a future privatised network is Mr
Richard Branson, chairman of Virgin, the entertainment and travel group.
Mr Rifkind said suggestions that his views on British Rail were at odds with
those of Mr Major were 'complete rubbish'. He added: 'John Major and I have
a very close shared view on what we would like to see happen.
'There has been no row in cabinet and it has not been discussed in cabinet.'
Conservative policy on the future of British Rail is now likely to be
detailed in the party's general election manifesto.
It appears that the party has shifted ground, bringing it closer to Labour
policy. Mr Rifkind suggested that both government subsidies and private
investment would run in tandem.
Mr John Prescott, shadow transport secretary, accused Mr Rifkind of having
'pinched' some of Labour's ideas. 'I do not mind private people coming in,'
he said. 'What I do worry about is safety.'
</TEXT>
