<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 92 / Rail charter hits funding problem
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH RAIL and the Department of Transport are this week likely to run
into criticisms that the long-delayed Passenger's Charter, due out on
Wednesday, has turned into a damp squib.
Earlier intentions of giving passengers an expanded system of compensation
for late and cancelled trains have foundered because neither BR nor the
government is prepared to fund it. Total compensation for late and cancelled
trains is unlikely to exceed the Pounds 6.5m in cash, travel vouchers and
season-ticket extensions handed out last year.
The main effect of the charter will be that BR's arbitrary and semi-secret
system of compensation will be restructured and publicised so that people
will know whether they are eligible for refunds.
BR has argued that without government funding an enhanced compensation
scheme could be financed only by higher fares or cuts in railway investment.
The Treasury, however, was not prepared to underwrite it.
Instead, a watered-down scheme will come into effect from May. The main
points in the modified scheme are: Compensation arrangements for people
making individual train journeys (as distinct from commuters) will be
virtually unchanged. If a train is cancelled or delayed unreasonably
passengers will not receive compensation automatically, but will be invited
to submit claims if they miss appointments or incur costs.
A self-financing 'insurance' scheme will be introduced, with business
passengers in mind. By paying a reservation fee in advance, travellers will
be entitled to an automatic refund of probably a third of their fare if
their train is cancelled or badly delayed.
Commuters will receive extensions to their season tickets for days on which
there is no effective service because of snow, industrial action or other
factors.
Commuters on poorly performing Network SouthEast routes will face lower
annual fare increases than commuters on recently modernised lines.
Each Network SouthEast route will be given its own target for punctuality
and reliability. If performance falls short of this, commuters with season
tickets will be given a discount on renewal. A similar scheme will apply for
Regional Railways commuters, but the performance target will be set for the
sector as a whole.
The RMT railworkers' union dismissed the charter as 'a political gimmick'.
It said that the solution to poor services was to give BR the financial
resources to improve quality.
</TEXT>
