<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 92 / Comparison of local taxation plans shows rich areas losing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VOTERS IN Bath, where Mr Chris Patten, the Tory party chairman, will defend
a slim 1,412 majority at the general election, would be among the biggest
losers under the government's proposed council tax.
According to the most detailed independent survey so far of the three
parties' local-taxation plans - published today  - if the council tax were
introduced this year adults in Bath would pay an extra Pounds 86. That would
be the biggest increase in England.
The study of the council tax, Labour's fair rates and the Liberal Democrats'
local income tax finds that each system results in wide variations in
average local tax bills for each adult at both regional and local-authority
levels.
Under the council tax, to be introduced next year if the Conservatives
retain power, the areas with high property values would tend to lose while
those with low values would gain.
But the size of the swings would not be as great as that under Labour's fair
rates or a local income tax.
By far the biggest losers under the proposals from the opposition parties
would be relatively wealthy areas.
The northern region of England, for example, would be the biggest winner
from Labour's plans, with each adult paying on average Pounds 82 less than
under the poll tax. Adults in Barrow-in-Furness would have to pay Pounds 183
less.
These gains would be made at the expense of Greater London and the
south-east where average bills would rise by Pounds 60 and Pounds 54
respectively. Each adult in south Buckinghamshire, for example, would have
to pay Pounds 178 more.
The local income tax proposed by the Liberal Democrats would produce the
lowest bills of the three options in metropolitan districts and inner London
boroughs, but would add most to bills in the south-east.
The study, produced for the Chartered Association of Certified Accountants,
is the first to estimate local tax levels for each adult in England under
the various options, and it includes the Pounds 140 universal cut in bills
announced in March last year.
It is based on published proposals for local taxation by the three main
parties, this year's grant allocation and government estimates of the
distribution of houses according to eight tax bands.
Mr Peter Smith of the University of York, the author of the report, says
that the contrast between the systems highlights the difficulty of balancing
equity against efficiency in local-government finance.
'There is in principle no reason why the two objectives . . . cannot be
addressed in such a system of local-government finance,' he says. 'However,
none of the systems currently proposed satisfactorily reconciles the
dichotomy.'
The report urges the setting up of a Royal Commission.
In Place of the Poll Tax. Chartered Association of Certified Accountants, 2
Woodside Place, Glasgow G3 7QP. Pounds 9.95.
</TEXT>
