FT  02 MAR 92 / Loophole continues to disrupt poll tax cases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TENS of thousands of court cases for poll tax non-payment are still
disrupted because of the confusion over the use of computer evidence before
magistrates, according to local authorities.
At a seminar last week organised by local authority associations, councils
reported that many cases had been withdrawn or adjourned until later this
month or beyond. This followed the ruling by magistrates in Coventry, upheld
by the High Court, that computer evidence was 'hearsay' and not admissible.
Ministers have emphasised that summonses could be issued for a date after
the legislation which will allow computer evidence is passed. The bill
ensuring this is due to become law in the next week or so.
The councils, however, suggest that in some areas the summonses have been
put off for longer than ministers advised.
Tory-controlled Croydon Borough Council decided not to issue 25,000
summonses, scheduled to be heard about now, after advice from the local
magistrates' clerk. These will not now be issued until next month for
hearing in May. Labour-controlled Birmingham withdrew 10,000 cases last week
and is issuing no more summonses 'until the law is clear'.
The government said last month that it would legislate to put the
admissibility of computer evidence beyond doubt - and decided to do so
through the bill to replace the poll tax with the council tax.
It refused to accept Labour's offer of co-operation on an emergency bill to
clear the Commons in a single day.
The difficulties will be highlighted on Wednesday, when the council tax bill
returns to the Commons and MPs get their first chance to discuss the issue
in detail.
Mr David Blunkett, Labour's local government spokesman, said: 'The figures
illustrate the devastating impact of the government's delay in closing the
computer-records loophole. Government dithering has brought poll tax debt
enforcement to a virtual standstill in many areas.'
He condemned as 'a travesty of the truth' ministerial attempts to blame
councils for difficulties in collecting the poll tax.
</TEXT>
