FT  02 MAR 92 / UK News (Employment): Watchdog criticises mortgage lenders
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MORTGAGE lenders are making the homes repossession crisis worse by insisting
on 'unrealistic' repayment schedules for borrowers in arrears, the National
Consumer Council said yesterday.
Many lenders failed to give borrowers struggling with repayments enough
help, according to the council, a government-funded watchdog. 'All too often
mortgage lenders do not contact customers in arrears until too late and, by
insisting on unrealistic repayment schemes, only make repossessions more
likely,' it said.
Its study follows last month's report from the Council of Mortgage Lenders
showing that more than 500,000 households were behind in mortgage payments.
Lady Wilcox, who chairs the consumer council, said mortgage lenders were 'in
business to help people buy homes, not to take their homes away from them'.
The lenders' council rejected the claim. 'It is not in the lenders'
interests to sit back and do nothing,' it said. 'Lenders are constantly
reviewing their policies.'
