FT  02 MAR 92 / UK News (Employment): BBC to decide in May on options for
future
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MANAGEMENT and governors of the BBC will decide on a range of options
for the future of the corporation in May in preparation for the
re-negotiation of its Royal Charter, which runs out at the end of 1996.
The range of possible options is being collated by a committee headed by Mr
Howell James, director of corporate affairs, and Ms Patricia Hodgson, head
of the corporation's policy unit. They are choosing from a list of options,
some contradictory and none of them costed, drawn up by 15 internal
committees set up last year to examine every aspect of the corporation's
future.
The proposals are believed to include the abolition of Radio 5, the
enhancement of BBC local radio and the recognition that in areas such as
drama and entertainment the BBC should be popular, but should not try to
match everything offered by the competition. Radio 3, it is suggested,
should end drama and concentrate on classical music, including live
performances, together with serious information and arts journalism.
Some of the committees' proposals have already been rejected and others have
received powerful backing in advance of a formal decision.
Sir Michael Checkland, the director-general, has rejected a proposal that
the corporation's orchestras should be privatised. He has argued that such
arts patronage is a central part of the corporation's role as a public
service broadcaster.
The BBC hopes to agree a blueprint for its future by late spring and publish
the document early in the autumn in order to open a public debate. The
debate is likely to be at its peak next year with the legislative process on
the Royal Charter getting under way in 1994.
</TEXT>
