<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 92 / UK News (Employment): Pressure rises on training budgets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CORPORATE training budgets are under increasing pressure because of the
recession, according to a survey published today by the Industrial Society.
Compared with a survey carried out by the society last September, the latest
survey of 486 companies shows that fewer companies expect training budgets
to rise over the next six months. The proportion is 32 per cent compared
with September's 38 per cent.
The society, an independent organisation which aims to foster improved
industrial relations, also notes a rise from 13 per cent to 24 per cent in
companies which expect budgets to decline.
The survey will contribute to the political debate over whether companies
should be forced to spend a fixed percentage of their payroll on training
employees.
The Labour party would introduce measures to ensure that each company sets
aside at least 0.5 per cent of pay. The Conservatives want to encourage
further spending, but would leave employers to decide the amount.
Deep cuts in training budgets in the last recession are widely viewed as one
of the most important contributors towards skill shortages in the late
1980s.
In another survey published today, the Wyatt company of consultants and
actuaries finds that a quarter of employees do not believe training in their
organisations adequate for the job. More than half thought their
organisation was ineffective in developing people.
In spite of the expected squeeze on future budgets, the Industrial Society
survey found that spending so far in the recession has held up well compared
with the economic downturn of the early 1980s.
It found that 40 per cent of companies spent more on training in the final
six months of last year than in the same period of 1990.
In explaining expected cuts in training budgets, 69 per cent cited
competitive pressure on costs, 55 per cent blamed shrinking staff numbers
and 41 per cent cited lower sales.
Industrial Society Training Survey, Number 4, Industrial Society, Robert
Hyde House, 48 Bryanston Square, London W1H 7LN, Pounds 20. Benchmark of
Attitudes to Work. Available from 071 222-8033. Pounds 30 excluding VAT.
</TEXT>
