<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 92 / UK News (Employment): IBM deals blow to computer leasing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE computer leasing industry is up in arms over a change in policy by
International Business Machines, the world's largest computer manufacturer,
which other companies believe threatens their ability to continue providing
customers with secondhand and rebuilt mainframe computers.
IBM has already taken legal action in the US against Comdisco, the largest
leasing company, claiming it has been 'counterfeiting' components in
computers sold to customers as IBM machines. It has now written to
customers, brokers and leasing companies in Europe warning them that
critical components in rebuilt IBM machines may also have been passed off as
being manufactured by IBM.
Such components could be more likely to fail than its own parts, IBM warns.
They would also not qualify under the company's maintenance agreement.
Customers, brokers and their bankers fear that the new policy could
adversely affect the price of used IBM equipment.
An immediate effect has been a doubling of the price of genuine IBM memory
cards - printed circuit boards bearing an array of semiconductor chips. The
cards, which store 128m bits of information, have risen in price from Pounds
100,000 to Pounds 200,000 in the past few months.
The row, although apparently esoteric, is critically important because of
the size and significance of the broking and leasing business. In Europe
alone it generates revenues of Dollars 10bn (Pounds 5.7bn) a year and is a
principal mechanism through which medium-sized and large businesses acquire
IBM mainframes. Refurbishing and refitting old machines to suit customers'
requirements is basic to the economics of the leasing business. Until now
IBM has approved this procedure and validated rebuilt machines.
Mr Geoffrey Sewell, director-general of the Birmingham-based European
Computer Leasing and Trading Association, said it was the most important
issue the leasing industry has faced since IBM user equipment was first
traded in the early 1970s. 'If IBM has its way, the net result will be that
within three years there will be no other source of new and secondhand
machines than IBM itself,' he said.
He added that IBM was right to be concerned that the integrity of its
products was not compromised, but that the rules should not be changed
retrospectively.
He wanted an amnesty on all equipment currently installed and running well,
while discussion continued between the association and IBM on a policy for
the future.
IBM's case against Comdisco in the US will be heard on April 15.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 5
</PAGE>
